glish Canada -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2019, the Quebec National Assembly passed Bill 21. It prohibits, among other things, certain state employees in positions of authority (including teachers, prison guards, police officers, and justices of the peace) from wearing religious symbols when providing public services. Many political commentators in English Canada denounced the law as running counter to Canadian multiculturalism and human rights. Why did the Quebec government adopt this particular form of state secularism? And why did it garner public support? The Challenges of a Secular Quebec analyzes the statute from different angles to provide a nuanced, respectful discussion of its intentions and principles that recognizes the province’s singular history in North America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aReligion and statezQuébec (Province). 7aRELIGION / Religion, Politics & State.2bisacsh1 aBaillargeon, Normand, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChevrier, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChouakri, Yasmina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerretti, Lucia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerretti, Lucia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGill, Charles-Étienne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLabelle, Micheline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLatour, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerin, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRocher, François, econtributor.4ctb4https:/